course_metadata.title: Adaptable and affordable housing for climate change adaptation

content_chunks.content: It is estimated that by 2050, the urban population will grow by another 2.5 billion. Climate action must start with housing because of its direct impact on people's health and livelihood. Building resilient and affordable homes for climate adaptation involves designing and building houses that can withstand and adapt to the challenges presented by climate change, and ensuring the safety and well-being of occupants. This digital course is designed to provide knowledge and practical skills in adaptable and affordable housing design solutions. It begins with the understanding about the role of housing against climate change, and further reviews a variety of solutions that can be used in design of adaptable housing, i.e., building with natural materials, installation of renewable energy systems, rainwater harvesting systems, waste-to-energy conversion. At the end of the course, community engagement is discussed and economic feasibility in terms of housing affordability is evaluated.

Climate-adaptive housing technology for resilient urban communities - this course delivers comprehensive expertise in designing and constructing affordable homes that withstand climate change challenges while promoting sustainable living. Students master natural building techniques including timber-based structures, green roof technology, and climate-resilient construction methods. The curriculum covers renewable energy integration, rainwater harvesting systems, waste-to-energy conversion technologies, and economic feasibility analysis for housing affordability. Graduates emerge equipped to develop adaptable housing solutions that address urban growth challenges, implement community engagement strategies, and create environmentally conscious housing that protects occupant health and livelihood while contributing to climate action initiatives.
